<title>
The intermediate filament network in cultured human keratinocytes is remarkably extensible and resilient.
</title>

<text>

<sections.0>
Introduction
ntermediate filaments are a diverse family of cytoskeletal proteins that assemble into 10 nm diameter filaments in cells[1]. hese filaments form a dense network throughout the cytoplasm of most animal cells, and in mammals, they are also found within the tough, epidermally-derived material alpha-keratin, which makes up structures such as hairs, horns, and claws[2]. nockout studies[3]β€“[6] and several characterized human genetic diseases[7] demonstrate that cells lacking their usual complement of intermediate filaments can be mechanically fragile, suggesting that intermediate filaments are important for maintaining the mechanical integrity of cells and tissues.
n spite of their importance to the mechanical integrity of cells, the mechanical properties of individual intermediate filaments and how they function within cytoskeletal networks in vivo are not well understood. ntermediate filaments in cells have been assumed to be stiff and fairly inextensible like their counterparts in hard keratins [8]β€“[10], but recent in vitro studies on single intermediate filaments and bundles suggest that they may be quite soft and remarkably extensible, stretching up to strains of 250%, or 3.5 times their original length before breaking[11]β€“[13]. ther in vitro studies have examined the mechanical properties of semi-dilute gels formed from suspensions of intermediate filaments[14]β€“[17]. hese experiments demonstrate that intermediate filament gels are softer, more extensible, and exhibit more extreme strain hardening than gels made from -actin or microtubules.
hile the tensile mechanics of single intermediate filaments and the mechanics of intermediate filament gels are not inconsistent with one another, emphasizing one or the other paints a very different picture of the mechanical function of intermediate filaments in cells and the design of the metazoan cytoskeleton in general. or example, a focus on the tensile properties of single filaments leads to questions about the morphology of the cytoskeleton and the mechanical conditions that might lead to intermediate filaments being loaded in tension and the kinds of deformations they typically experience. n contrast, a focus on the properties of semi-dilute gels assumes that intermediate filaments contribute to cell elasticity via entropic mechanisms in which individual filaments and filament bundles are never loaded directly in tension. hich approach is more relevant to the in vivo condition likely depends on the magnitude of cell deformation. t small cell strains, intermediate filament are likely to be found in a tortuous conformation, and therefore entropic gel models are appropriate. t larger strains, however, individual filaments and bundles in the network could be pulled taut, in which case the tensile properties would be more relevant.
n this study, we aimed to answer the following questions: 1. hat happens to the morphology of the intermediate filament network as cells are deformed? 2. s it possible to deform cells to the point where intermediate filaments are straightened and presumably loaded in tension? 3. f so, are these deformations physiologically relevant, i.e. do the cells survive? 4. t what magnitude of cell strain, if any, does the intermediate filament network show signs of damage?
