Results and iscussion
eratinocytes remained attached to the membrane during and after the stretching protocol and showed only minor loss of adhesion after large-scale uniaxial deformations (ig. 1). ne way of measuring the loss of adhesion between the cells and the silastic substrate is to measure the amount of cell compression after the membrane is returned to its relaxed state. he average compression strain for cells after a maximum strain of 126% was β�’2%, which suggests that loss of adhesion was minimal. n addition to remaining attached at such high strains, most keratinocytes also retained their structural integrity and remained viable, as measured using the vital inclusion dye fluorescein diacetate and the vital exclusion dye  (ig. 2). iability decreased significantly (p<0.001) with increasing cell strain, but remarkably, most cells still survived even the highest strains we subjected them to.
